elements.content: To investigate the influences of the geometries of pendant carboxylate ligands and some intramolecular/intermolecular weak interactions on the structures of transition metal complexes, five new Cd(II) complexes, Cd2(HL )2(L )4 (1), Cd2(HL 1 )2(L )4 (2), {[Cd2(HL 1 )(L )4(H2O)2](H2O)}∞ (3), [Cd(L 1 )(L )]∞ (4), and Cd2(L 1 )2(HL 1 )2(L 4 )2 (5) (HL 1 = 3-(2-pyridyl)pyrazole, HL 2 = benzoic acid, HL 3 = naphthalene-carboxylic acid, HL 4 = 9-anthracene-carboxylic acid, and HL 5 = isonicotinic acid), have been synthesized and structurally characterized by elemental analyses, IR spectroscopy, and single-crystal X-ray diffraction analyses. 1 and 2 have a similar dinuclear structure, which is further assembled to form a one-dimensional (1D) chain by π···π stacking and/or hydrogen-bonding interactions. 3 possesses a 1D chain structure that is further interlinked via intermolecular π···π stacking, resulting in a two-dimensional (2D) network, while 4 has a 2D (4,4) network with channel dimension of 9.34 × 9.34 Å2 and further assembles into a three-dimensional (3D) network by interlayer π···π stacking. 5 also possesses a dinuclear structure and then forms a 2D network through intermolecular π···π stacking and C−H···O hydrogen-bonding interactions. Interestingly, 3 and 5 were obtained simultaneously in the same reaction system. The structural differences of those complexes show the influences of the geometries of the pendant carboxylate ligands. This result also shows that intramolecular/intermolecular weak interactions play important roles in the formation of coordination architectures, especially in the aspect of linking multinuclear discrete subunits or low-dimensional entities into high-dimensional supramolecular frameworks. In addition, complexes 1, 2, and 4 exhibit blue emission in the solid state at room temperature.

Introduction

Metallosupramolecular species built from transition metal ions and organic bridging ligands have been rapidly developed in recent years because of their fascinating structural diversities and potential applications as functional materials. The rational design and synthesis of coordination architectures (discrete and polymeric) with metal ions (or metal clusters) and organic ligands is still at an evolutionary stage with the current focus mainly on understanding the factors to determine the crystal packing. In addition to coordination bonding, some weak interactions, such as hydrogen bonding and π⋅⋅⋅π stacking interactions also greatly affect the structures of coordination complexes, and they may link multinuclear discrete subunits or low-dimensional entities into high-dimensional supramolecular networks. In this regard, the skillful combination of bridging carboxylates, 2,2‘-bipyridyl-like chelating ligands, and metal ions have generated many interesting coordination architectures. As bridging ligands, the geometries of different pendant carboxylate groups may play profound roles in adjusting the topologies of their transition metal complexes. On the other hand, 2,2‘-bipyridyl-like ligands are bidentate chelating ligands, which can commonly act as terminal ligands, and also may provide supramolecular interaction sites for molecular recognition or assembly. Moreover, luminescent organic compounds and coordination complexes have been an active research area for decades because of their various potential applications in material science, in which stable blue luminescent coordination complexes that are useful in electroluminescent devices are still not common and still challenging to be prepared.

elements.content: Considering all the aspects stated above, our idea is to prepare and tune these kinds of complexes by carefully selecting three kinds of ligands (Chart ):  (a) a 2,2‘-bipyridyl-like chelating ligand, 3-(2-pyridyl)pyrazole (HL 1 ), with an N−H entity as a hydrogen-bonding donor, (b) three structurally related pendant carboxylate ligands [benzoic acid (HL 2 ), naphthalene-carboxylic acid (HL 3 ), and 9-anthracene-carboxylic acid (HL 4 )] with different aromatic skeletons, and (c) one ditopic bridging ligand, isonicotinic acid (HL 5 ) who contains similar size aromatic skeleton with that of HL 2 . In this report, five new Cd(II) coordination complexes with these ligands, Cd2(HL 1 )2(L 2 )4 (1), Cd2(HL 1 )2(L 3 )4 (2), {[Cd2(HL 1 )(L 4 )4(H2O)2](H2O)}∞ (3), [Cd(L 1 )(L 5 )]∞ (4), and Cd2(L 1 )2(HL 1 )2(L 4 )2 (5), were synthesized and structurally determined by X-ray analysis. In these complexes, the pendant carboxylate ligands are able to link Cd(II) ions in various modes, giving rise to dinuclear, one- or two-dimensional Cd(II) complexes, and show single O-terminal bidentate chelating and μ3 chelating/bridging coordination modes, respectively.

X-ray Data Collection and Structure Determinations. X-ray single-crystal diffraction data for complexes 1−5 were collected on a Bruker Smart 1000 CCD diffractometer at 293(2) K with Mo−Kα radiation (λ = 0.71073 Å) by ω scan mode. The program SAINT was used for integration of the diffraction profiles. Semiempirical absorption corrections were applied using SADABS program. All the structures were solved by direct methods using the SHELXS program of the SHELXTL package and refined by full-matrix least-squares methods with SHELXL. Metal atoms in each complex were located from the E-maps, and other non-hydrogen atoms were located in successive difference Fourier syntheses and refined with anisotropic thermal parameters on F 2. The hydrogen atoms of the ligand were generated theoretically onto the specific atoms and refined isotropically with fixed thermal factors. For 3, part of hydrogen atoms of water were added by the Fourier differences maps and refined isotropically. elements.content: Description of Crystal Structures. Cd 2 (HL 1 ) 2 (L 2 ) 4 1. 1 has a centrosymmetric dinuclear structure (Figure a) with the Cd(II) ion seven-coordinated by two N atoms from one chelating HL 1 ligand and five O atoms from three L 2 ligands. HL 1 acts as a typical chelating ligand coordinating to the Cd(II) ion with the Cd−N bond distances ranging from 2.369(2) to 2.339(2) Å and the N−Cd−N angle being 70.1(8)°. For L 2 , there exists two different coordination modes with Cd(II) ion; namely, one [O(3), O(4)] chelates with Cd(1) bidentately, while the other [O(1), O(2)] adopts a μ3 chelating-bridging coordination mode to connect two Cd(II) ions [i.e., Cd(1) and Cd(1A)] to form a dinuclear structure [Cd(1)···Cd(1A) distance is 3.890 Å]. The Cd−O distances [2.3141(2)−2.5984(2) Å] are quite similar to normal Cd−OCO bond distances [2.251−2.879 Å]. The Cd(1)−O(1) bond distance [2.5984(19) Å] is obviously longer than Cd(1)−O(2) [2.3141(18) Å], suggesting that carboxylic group coordination modes are asymmetric, and this is common in μ3 carboxylic metal coordination. Also, all these Cd−N, Cd−O bond distances and the bond angles around each Cd(II) center are in the normal range expected for such coordination complexes (Table ). It is worth noting that N(3) atom of HL 1 is not coordinated to Cd(II) ions, which presents a strong intramolecular hydrogen-bonding interactions with coordinated O(3A) atom of L 2 ligand [the N(3)···O(3A) separation is 2.772 Å, N(3)−H(3A)···O(3A) angle is 171°, symmetry code A = −x + 1, −y + 1, −z] (Table ).

elements.content: Thermogravimetric Analysis. Complexes 1, 2, and 4 are stable at ambient conditions, and thermogravimetric experiments were performed to explore their thermal stabilities. The TGA curves of 1 and 2 are similar, probably due to their structural similarity. For 1, there are two separate two-step weight loss steps. The first weight loss of 27.4% occurs from 215 to 268 °C, which is attributed to the loss of coordinated one HL 1 and one L 2 ligands (calcd. 26.71%). The second weight loss of 49.1% from 390 to 600 °C corresponds to the loss of all the remaining ligands (calcd. 49.89%). The remaining weight of 23.6% corresponds to the percentage (23.11%) of the Cd and O components, indicating that the final product is CdO. For 2, the first weight loss of 28.7% occurs from 200 to 310 °C (peaking at 256 °C), which corresponds to one HL 1 and one L 3 (calcd. 28.42%). The following two-step weight loss of about 60.1% between 340 and 600 °C corresponds to other coordinated HL 1 and L 3 ligands. As for 4, the TGA measurements indicate that the 2D networks remain stable upon heating until a series of complicated weight losses starting from 126 °C and not ending until 800 °C.

elements.content: Luminescent Properties of 1, 2, and 4. The luminescent properties of 1, 2, and 4 were investigated in the solid state at room temperature. As indicated in Figure , complexes 1, 2, and 4 exhibit strong blue emissions. The emission maxima (λ max) are 359 (1), 380 (2), and 442 nm (4) (λ ex = 300 nm for 1 and 332 nm for 2 and 4), respectively, which may be due to σ-donation from the coordination environments of the Cd(II) centers and could be assigned as ligand-to-metal charge-transfer (LMCT). In comparison with 1, it is worth noting that 4 has a remarkable lower energy emission shift, which may originate from the obvious decrease of the electron density of the pendant carboxylate ligand of 4 affected by the electron-withdrawing N donor of HL 5 ligand relative to HL 2 and is in line with the energy of π* orbital. Those complexes may be used as a potential material for blue-light emitting diode devices and may be an candidate for thermally stable and solvent-resistant blue fluorescent material.

elements.content: Five new Cd(II) complexes with mixed bridging and chelating ligands have been synthesized under hydrothermal conditions exhibiting a systematic structural variation of coordination architectures by the employment of different pendant carboxylate and the auxiliary 3-(2-pyridyl)pyrazole ligands. These results show that the topologies of such complexes could be adjusted by the geometries of pendant carboxylate ligands. Meanwhile, some intramolecular/intermolecular weak interactions, such as hydrogen bonding and π···π stacking interactions, also play important roles in the formation of complexes, especially further linking the discrete subunits and low-dimensional entities into high-dimensional supramolecular networks. Moreover, the complexes 1, 2, and 4 display strong blue emissions at room temperature.
elements.clean_text:
Conclusion

Five new Cd(II) complexes with mixed bridging and chelating ligands have been synthesized under hydrothermal conditions exhibiting a systematic structural variation of coordination architectures by the employment of different pendant carboxylate and the auxiliary 3-(2-pyridyl)pyrazole ligands. These results show that the topologies of such complexes could be adjusted  by the geometries of pendant carboxylate ligands. Meanwhile, some intramolecular/intermolecular weak interactions, such as hydrogen bonding and π⋅⋅⋅π stacking interactions, also play important roles in the formation of complexes, especially further linking the discrete subunits and low-dimensional entities into high-dimensional supramolecular networks. Moreover, the complexes 1, 2, and 4 display strong blue emissions at room temperature.
